COMMUNITY

Urban Gardening in Yarra

 

The Urban Agricultural Strategy released by the Yarra City Council has addressed the numerous activities undertaken by local communities to combat and prepare for scarcity in resources and highlighted the benefits associated with pursuing urban agricultural ventures as a community to safeguard the population and thrive even through times of difficulty.

The adjoining graph represents the different community gardens and sustainable groups set up across the city of Yarra in response to the Urban Agricultural Strategy and initiative encouraged by the Council and its representatives. Feel free to explore some of them by clicking the button below.

Explore your options in the City of Yarra

Planter Boxes

Accessing Planter Boxes

The council of Yarra conveniently allows for residents and communities to set up Planter boxes, provided consideration is given to : 

  • Pedestrian Movement 
  • Parking 
  • Visibility  
  • Street Sweepers.

Distance from Infrastructure

The council advises against the setting up of planter boxes between infrastructure and a property/boundary line (for example between a public seating bench and a property line)

Also pay heed to :

Distance to Intersection

A planter box cannot be installed within 7m of an intersection 

Distance to Curb/Footpath 

  • A footpath planter box must maintain a 0.4m buffer to the edge of any curb.
  • Maintain a minimum footpath width of 1.5m from the property line directly across the footpath. 
Steps to Apply for a Planter Box

LANEWAY GARDENS

Ensuring suitability for Laneway Gardens

To assess if your laneway is suitable to host a pop-up garden, consideration should be given to: 

  • Existing use of the laneway
  • Vehicular or pedestrian access requirements 
  • Type of laneway
  • Proximity to services
Types of Laneways in Yarra

Whether a laneways is suitable to host a pop-up garden is determined by the type of laneway, of which there are 3 categories : 

  • Type A
A laneway that is extensively used by abutting properties for regular vehicular access generally prohibits the use of it for pop-up gardens, due to the inconvenience faced by community members.
  • Type B
A laneway that is used by abutting properties for intermittent vehicular access, access to off-street garages or carports generally allows for the setting up of pop-up gardens conditional to the ease in which partial or occasional access is granted to the community members. 
  • Type C
A laneway that is irregularly or unused by abutting properties for vehicular access, access to off-street garages or carports generally allows for the setting up of pop-up gardens conditional to the ease in which partial or occasional access is granted to the community members as needed. 
Steps to Apply for a Laneway Garden

EDIBLE TREES

Edible Trees in Public Spaces

A grassy or mulched garden around you can act as an ideal location to plant edible (fruit and vegetable) trees. 

Avoiding nature strips to grow edible trees is not advised, due to the poor soil and limited availability of water. 

Responsibilities
  • To maintain your edible trees as well as the area immediately surrounding it – this includes tools required, watering, pruning and harvesting.
  • If the area is not maintained, the council has the right to remove the tree. 
  • Excess fees occurring as a result of possible claims against the garden would be the growers responsibility 
  • (Although the Council provides a public liability insurance that the resident can avail)
Steps to Apply for an Edible Tree
